{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:11:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:11:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.22,0.04,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75120"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60628"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8414"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75120"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlial cells play a crucial role in the central nervous system\u0027s response to injury. When activated, these cells release various inflammatory mediators.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations of molecules is produced by activated glial cells during neuroinflammation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nitric oxide, reactive oxygen species and prostaglandins","Nitric oxide and reactive oxygen species","Prostaglandins and leukotrienes","Nitric oxide, reactive oxygen species and acetylcholine","Reactive oxygen species and prostaglandins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring neuroinflammation, activated glial cells (primarily microglia and astrocytes) produce \u003Cstrong\u003Enitric oxide, reactive oxygen species and prostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E. These inflammatory mediators contribute to both protective and potentially harmful effects in the injured brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitric oxide and reactive oxygen species\u003C/strong\u003E is incomplete as it omits prostaglandins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandins and leukotrienes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it omits key oxidative mediators and includes leukotrienes which are primarily produced by leukocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitric oxide, reactive oxygen species and acetylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because acetylcholine is a neurotransmitter produced by neurons, not glial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive oxygen species and prostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E is incomplete as it omits nitric oxide, which is produced via the inducible nitric oxide synthase pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe neuroinflammatory response involves complex interactions between different types of glial cells and neurons. While this response can help clear debris and promote repair, excessive or prolonged inflammation may contribute to secondary injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Activated glial cells produce inflammatory mediators including nitric oxide, reactive oxygen species and prostaglandins in response to injury.","Microglia and astrocytes are the main glial cells involved in neuroinflammation.","The neuroinflammatory response can be both protective and harmful in brain injury."],"references":["Suzumura A. Immune Response in the Brain: Glial Response and Cytokine Production. NeuroImmune Biology. 2008;6:289\u2013303. doi: 10.1016/S1567-7443(07)10014-4. Epub 2008 Jul 12. PMCID: PMC7185635.","Parpura V, Heneka MT, Montana V, Oliet SH, Schousboe A, Haydon PG, Stout RF Jr, Spray DC, Reichenbach A, Pannicke T, Pekny M, Pekna M, Zorec R, Verkhratsky A. Glial cells in (patho)physiology. J Neurochem. 2012 Apr;121(1):4-27. doi: 10.1111/j.1471-4159.2012.07664.x. Epub 2012 Feb 2. PMID: 22251135; PMCID: PMC3304021.","J\u00e4kel S, Dimou L. Glial Cells and Their Function in the Adult Brain: A Journey through the History of Their Ablation. Front Cell Neurosci. 2017 Feb 13;11:24. doi: 10.3389/fncel.2017.00024. PMID: 28243193; PMCID: PMC5303749."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60628"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T23:06:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:07:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9150"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75120"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedA